\vspace*{-15pt}

\section{Introduction}

In this diagram, similar to Figure 5.2 on page 23 of the ATBD, I have
added the instrument and tangent vectors, and the third column of the
ECR-to-FOV matrix.  \\[-15pt]

\begin{centering}
\includegraphics[scale=0.9,angle=270]{wvs-157-circ}\\[10pt]
\end{centering}

The third column of {\tt ECR_to_FOV} is a vector $\vec{F}$, in ECR, along
the line of sight.

Let $\vec{R}_s$ be the spacecraft position vector and $\vec{T}$ be the
tangent position vector (both in ECR).

There are (at least) four ways to define the plane of the line-of-sight
frame (LOSF).

\begin{itemize}

\item The plane normal to $\vec{N} = \vec{R}_s \times \vec{T}$.

\item The plane normal to $\vec{N} = \vec{R}_s \times \vec{F}$.

\item The plane normal to $\vec{N} = \vec{F} \times \vec{T}$.

\item The plane normal to $\vec{N} = \vec{F} \times \vec{G}$, where
$\vec{G} = -\nabla E(\lambda_t,\phi_t,0)$, $E$ is the Earth reference
ellipsoid, and $[\lambda_t,\phi_t,0]^T$ is the sub-tangent point .

\end{itemize}

EMLS uses the first definition.  The angle between the unit vector
$\hat{n} = \frac{\vec{N}}{|\vec{N}|}$ and the north pole is the orbit
inclination angle $\beta$.  If the orbit is not nearly equatorial, $\cos
\beta = \hat{n}_3$ may be used, but this can have significant error for a
nearly-equatorial orbit (see \h{wvs-154}).

In the first three cases, in a three-dimensional model, the plane does not
contain $\vec{G}$ unless the orbit is polar or equatorial.  The plane does
contain the center of the Earth.

In the fourth case, the plane is a \emph{normal section}, as described in
Section \ref{146-Normal-Section} in \h{wvs-146}.

The forward model calculates the refraction-corrected
$\chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}}$ angle as

\begin{equation}\label{one}
\sin \chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}} = \frac{N_t}{N_s} \frac{H_t}{H_s}
\text{ where } H_t = | \vec{H}_t | \text{ and } H_s = | \vec{H}_s | \,.
\end{equation}

\section{Calculations for EMLS}

The routines in {\tt get_chi_angles_m} calculate $H_s = R_s + 38.9014\,
\sin 2(\phi_t-51^\circ\hspace{-4.2pt}.\hspace{1pt}6814 )$ and remark that
this is an empirical formula, which depends upon the orbit inclination,
which is unique to each instrument, and, indeed, different for every MAF
of SMLS.

Two lines above Equation (8.5) in the ATBD, there is the formula
$\vec{H}_s = \vec{R}_s - \vec{d}$, where the co\"ordinates of $\vec{d}$ in
LOSF are defined by Equation (5.22):

\begin{equation}\begin{split}\label{two}
\vec{d} = \,& \left[ \left( N(\phi_t) - H_t^\oplus \right) \cos \phi_t,
                 \left( \frac{c^2}{a^2} N(\phi_t) - H_t^\oplus \right)
                 \sin \phi_t, 0 \right] \text{ where} \\
R_{\text{eq}}^\oplus \equiv \,& H_t^\oplus = N(\phi_t) \,
 \sqrt{ \sin^2 \phi_t + \frac{c^4}{a^4} \cos^2 \phi_t }\,,\\
N(\phi) = \,& \frac{a^2}{\sqrt{a^2 \cos^2 \phi + c^2 \sin^2 \phi}}
        = \frac{a}{\sqrt{1-e^2\sin^2\phi_t}}
 \text{ is the radius in the prime vertical} \\
 \,& \text{ (see Equation (\ref{146-RN}) in \h{wvs-146}) at geodetic angle } \phi
  \text{ in the LOSF, and } \phi_t \\
 \,& \text{ is the geodetic tangent angle in the LOSF.} \\
\end{split}\end{equation}

Combining the last two equations,

\begin{equation}\label{Req}
R_{\text{eq}}^\oplus \equiv H_t^\oplus =
 \sqrt{\frac{a^4 \sin^2 \phi_t + c^4 \cos^2 \phi_t}
            {a^2 \cos^2 \phi_t + c^2 \sin^2 \phi_t}} \,.
\end{equation}

Equations (\ref{two}) and (\ref{Req}) are incorrect.  A term involving
$\frac{\d N(\phi)}{\d \phi}$ was omitted in the derivation.  The correct
result is derived in \h{wvs-146} in Equation (\ref{146-principal-geod}) in
Section \ref{146-Geod}, and displayed again in Section \ref{146-Prime}:

\begin{equation}\label{Correct}
R_{\text{eq}}^\oplus = R_M = a\,\frac{1-e^2}
                                     {(1-e^2 \sin^2 \phi_t)^\frac32} \,,
\end{equation}

where eccentricity $e = 1 - \frac{c^2}{a^2}$.

From the figure, $\vec{H}_t = \vec{R}_t - \vec{d}$, where $\vec{R}_t =
\vec{T} - (\vec{T} \cdot \hat{n})\, \hat{n}$ is the projection of
$\vec{T}$ into the LOSF.

The semi-minor axis of the Earth-projected ellipse in the LOSF is given by
Equation (5.2):

\begin{equation}
c^2 = \frac{a^2 b^2}{a^2 \sin^2 \beta + b^2 \cos^2 \beta}
\end{equation}

where $a$ and $b$ are the semi-major and semi-minor axes of the Earth.

The geocentric tangent angle $\gamma_t$ is the angle between $\vec{T}$ and
$\vec{Q}$, where $\vec{Q} = \pm \hat{z} \times \hat{n}$ are the directions
of the intersections of the Earth-projected ellipse with the equatorial
plane.  Having $\gamma_t$, one can calculate the geodetic tangent angle
$\phi_t$ in the LOSF using $c^2 \tan \phi = a^2 \tan \gamma_t$ or Equation
(5.4) in the ATBD:

\begin{equation}\begin{split}
\sin \phi_t = \,& \frac{a^2 \sin \gamma_t}
                       {\sqrt{a^4 \sin^2 \gamma_t + c^4 \cos^2 \gamma_t}}
                       \text{ and} \\
\cos \phi_t = \,& \frac{c^2 \cos \gamma_t}
                       {\sqrt{a^4 \sin^2 \gamma_t + c^4 \cos^2 \gamma_t}}\,. \\
\end{split}\end{equation}

This depends upon the quadrant of $\gamma_t$, which depends upon the sign
chosen for $\vec{Q}$.  The normal to the Earth-projected ellipse at the
tangent point, in LOSF, is given by Equation (5.7) in the ATBD:

\begin{equation}
\vec{n}_d = [\, -\sin \phi_t,\, \cos \phi_t,\, 0\, ]\,.
\end{equation}

The coordinates of $\vec{n}_d$ are in LOSF.  Let $A$ be $\vec{n}_d$ in
ECR, $\hat{q} = \frac{\vec{Q}}{|\vec{Q}|}$, $\hat{y} =\hat{n} \times
\hat{q}$, and $\mathbf{M}$ be the matrix whose columns are $\hat{q}$,
$\hat{y}$, and $\hat{n}$.  Then $\mathbf{M} \vec{A} = \vec{n}_d$.

The quadrant of $\phi_t$ can be chosen to minimize the angle between
$\vec{A}$ and $\vec{R}_t$.  Having $\phi_t$ in the correct quadrant allows
to calculate $\vec{d}$, and then $\vec{H}_t$ and $\vec{H}_s$, and then
$\chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}}$.

\section{Calculations in three dimensions}

The tangent point can be expressed in geodetic co\"ordinates $(\lambda_t,
\phi_t, h_t)$ corresponding to the tangent point $\vec{T}$ in ECR
co\"ordinates.

The position $\vec{T}_0$ of the sub-tangent point on the surface of the
Earth is defined to have geodetic co\"ordinates $(\lambda_t, \phi_t, 0)$. 
The ECR co\"ordinates $(x_t, y_t, z_t)$ of $\vec{T}_0$ can be calculated
from those geodetic co\"ordinates using equations from section
\ref{146-Rel} \h{wvs-146}.  Using $\rho^2_t = x^2_t + y^2_t$, the equation
of the ellipsoid can be written

\begin{equation}\label{Ellipsoid}
E_{T_0} = x^2_t + y^2_t + \frac{z^2_t}{1-e^2}
        = \rho^2_t + \frac{z^2_t}{1-e^2} = a^2 \,,
\end{equation}

where eccentricity $e = 1 - \frac{b^2}{a^2}$, $a$ is the equatorial radius
of the Earth, and $b$ is the polar radius.  From Equation
(\ref{Ellipsoid}), $z^2_t = ( 1 - e^2 ) ( a^2 - \rho^2_t )$.  The inward
normal to the Earth reference ellipsoid $E$ at $\vec{T}_0$, is

\begin{equation}\begin{split}\label{Gradient}
\vec{G}_{T_0} = -\,& \nabla E_{T_0} =
   - \left[ 2x_t, 2y_t, \frac{2z_t}{1-e^2} \right]^T
 = - \left[ 2x_t, 2y_t, 2 \sqrt{( 1 - e^2 ) ( a^2 - \rho^2_t )} \right]^T
 \,, \\
 \text{ and }
|\vec{G}_{T_0}| =\,& 2\,\sqrt{\frac{a^2-\rho^2_t}{1-e^2}} \,.
\end{split}\end{equation}

$\vec{G}_{T_0}$ is parallel to $\vec{H}_t$.  Let $\hat{g}_{T_0} =
\frac{\vec{G}_{T_0}}{|\vec{G}_{T_0}|} = [ \xi_t, \eta_t, \zeta_t ]^T$ be
the inward unit normal at $T_0$. Then

\begin{equation}
\vec{d} = \vec{T}_0 + R_{\text{eq}}^\oplus\, \hat{g}_{T_0} \,.
\end{equation}


The vector $\vec{R}_s$ is the geocentric position of the instrument.  The
height of the instrument, measured from the center of the equivalent
circular Earth is $H_s = | \vec{R}_s - \vec{d} |$.  The height of the
tangent point, measured from the center of the equivalent
circular Earth is $H_t = R_{\text{eq}}^\oplus + h_t$.  From the figure,

\begin{equation}\label{Chi}
\sin \chi_{\text{eq}} = \frac{H_t}{H_s} =
  \frac{H_t}{\sqrt{H_t^2+s^2}} = \sqrt{1-(\vec{F}\cdot\vec{g})^2}
  \,.
\end{equation}

The refracted $\chi$ angle is given by Equation (\ref{one}), \emph{viz.}

\begin{equation}
\sin \chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}} =
 \frac{\mathcal{N}_t}{H_t}\sin \chi_{\text{eq}} =
 \frac{\mathcal{N}_t H_t}{\mathcal{N}_s H_s} =
 \frac{\mathcal{N}_t}{\mathcal{N}_s} \frac{H_t}{\sqrt{H_t^2+s^2}} =
 \frac{\mathcal{N}_t}{\mathcal{N}_s} \sqrt{1-(\vec{F}\cdot\vec{g})^2} \,.
\end{equation}

By using $\cos\chi_{\text{eq}} = \vec{F}\cdot\vec{g}$, neither $H_s$ nor
$s$ are required.

% From Equation (A.4) in the ATBD, calculating the refracted path length
% requires $H_s$.  Therefore, the tangent form in Equation (\ref{Chi}) is
% probably not useful when refraction is to be taken into account.

If the fourth definition of the LOSF is used, $R_{\text{eq}}^\oplus$ would be
the radius of curvature of the normal section, as described in Equation
(\ref{146-Req}) in section \ref{146-Normal-Section}, or Equation
(\ref{146-Req2}) in section \ref{146-NoAz}, in \h{wvs-146}.

The derivative of $\chi_\text{eq}^\text{refr}$ with respect to $H_t$ is
also needed.

\begin{equation}
\frac{\text{d} \chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}} }{ \text{d} H_t}
  \cos \chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}} =
  \sin \chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}}
  \left[ \frac1{\mathcal{N}_t}
         \frac{\text{d} \mathcal{N}_t}{\text{d} H_t} +
         \frac{s^2}{(H_t^2+s^2) H_t} \right].
\end{equation}

From the figure, $\frac{s^2}{\sqrt{H_t^2+s^2}} = \cos^2
\chi_\text{eq} = ( \vec{F}\cdot\vec{g} )^2$.  Then

\begin{equation}
\frac{\text{d} \chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}} }{ \text{d} H_t}
  \cos \chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}} =
  \sin \chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}}
  \left[ \frac1{\mathcal{N}_t}
         \frac{\text{d} \mathcal{N}_t}{\text{d} \zeta_t}
         \frac{\text{d} \zeta_t}{\text{d} H_t} +
         \frac{\cos^2\chi_\text{eq}}{H_t} \right] =
  \sin \chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}}
  \left[ \frac1{\mathcal{N}_t}
         \frac{\text{d} \mathcal{N}_t}{\text{d} \zeta_t}
         \frac{\text{d} \zeta_t}{\text{d} H_t} +
         \frac{( \vec{F}\cdot\vec{g} )^2}{H_t} \right].
\end{equation}

We have

\begin{equation}\label{dndz}
\mathcal{N}_t = 1 + a\, e^{-\zeta_t \ln 10} ~\Rightarrow~ 
  \frac{ \text{d} \mathcal{N}_t }{ \text{d} \zeta_t } =
   - \ln 10 ( \mathcal{N}_t - 1 ) \,.
\end{equation}

Therefore

\begin{equation}
\frac{\text{d} \chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}} }{ \text{d} H_t}
  \cos \chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}} =
  \sin \chi^{\text{refr}}_{\text{eq}}
  \left[\frac{( \vec{F}\cdot\vec{g} )^2}{H_t}  -
         \ln 10\, \frac{\mathcal{N}_t-1}{\mathcal{N}_t}
         \frac{\text{d} \zeta_t}{\text{d} H_t} \right].
\end{equation}

By using $\cos\chi_{\text{eq}} = \vec{F}\cdot\vec{g}$, neither $H_s$ nor
$s$ are required.

